Year = {1994},
Volume = {192},
Number = {1-2},
Pages = {99-116},
Abstract = {The myiophilous pollination syndrome of stapeliads is investigated.
   Olfactory stimuli, imitating dung or decaying organic (zoogenic or
   phytogenic) matter, are used as attractants, together with mimetic
   colouration and, sometimes mimetic sculpturing. In most species nectar
   is present. The nectar mainly serves as optical attractant causing
   brilliance effects, and as visitor guide. However, nectar obviously is
   also a reward in many species. Flies (Cyclorrhapha: Calyptratae)
   constitute the most important pollinating group. In the pollination
   process they carry pollinaria only at the distal parts of their
   proboscis, never on their legs. No fundamental differences between the
   pollinator spectra of flowers in habitat and cultivated ones were
   observed.},
